a means to a living, but as an essential part of a meaningful life. Central among Deutsch’s arguments for the necessity of bookstores is the incalculable value of browsing—since, when we are deep in the act of looking at the shelves, we move through space as though we are inside the mind itself, immersed in self-reflection.In the age of one-click shopping, this is no ordinary defense of bookstores, but rather an urgent account of why they are essential places of discovery, refuge, and fulfillment—and how they enrich the communities that are lucky enough to have them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBooks and readingxSocial aspects. 0aBooksellers and booksellingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBooksellers and booksellingzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aBookstoresxSocial aspects. 0aBookstoreszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh  aAcademic publishing.  aAdmiration.  aAdvocacy.  aAisle.  aAnalects.  aAnalogy.  aAuthor.  aBeth Medrash Govoha.  aBookselling.  aBrowsing.  aBusiness case.  aCIVICUS.  aCautionary tale.  aCharles Simic.  aCleanliness.  aCoffeehouse.  aCommodity.  aCommonplace book.  aCompetitive advantage.  aCondition of possibility.  aConvenience.  aCultural artifact.  aCultural institution.  aCustomer.  aDecorum.  aDemocratic Vistas.  aDivine soul.  aEdition (book).  aElizabeth Hardwick (writer).  aEncyclopedic knowledge.  aEnthusiasm.  aExchange value.  aFinancial statement.  aGenerosity.  aGovernance.  aGrand opening.  aGratitude.  aGreeting card.  aGreeting.  aGross margin.  aHer Secret Is Patience.  aHigh culture.  aHonorarium.  aHorace Walpole.  aHumility.  aHumour.  aHygiene.  aIdealism.  aIllustration.  aImagination.  aInco